# Implement `aggregate/2` for `TimeSeriesResampler`

The module below is complete except for the private helper `aggregate/2`, whose
body has been replaced with `# TODO`. Your job is to implement `aggregate/2`.

## What `aggregate/2` must do

`aggregate/2` reduces the data points that fall inside a single bucket down to
one aggregated value, according to the chosen aggregation mode.

- **Signature:** `defp aggregate(points, mode)` where `points` is a **non-empty**
  list of `{timestamp_ms, value}` tuples and `mode` is one of
  `:last | :first | :mean | :sum | :count | :max | :min`.
- **Invariant you may rely on:** `points` is already sorted **ascending by
  timestamp** (the caller sorts the full dataset before grouping), so the head
  of the list is the earliest point and the last element is the latest.
- **Return value:** a single number (the aggregated value for the bucket).

Implement one clause per mode:

- `:last` — the `value` of the latest timestamp in the bucket (the last element).
- `:first` — the `value` of the earliest timestamp in the bucket (the head).
- `:count` — the number of data points in the bucket (an integer).
- `:sum` — the sum of all values in the bucket.
- `:mean` — the arithmetic mean of all values in the bucket, as a float
  (i.e. use `/` division so the result is a float).
- `:max` — the maximum value among the points.
- `:min` — the minimum value among the points.

